Intraparenchymal hemorrhage is absent but there is evidence of blood in the extra-axial fluid spaces layering predominately on the left side of the tentorium.  The prominent subdural collections over both frontal and anterior temporal convexities are slightly higher in density than CSF suggesting either increased protein or even a small amount of hemorrhage into spaces; however, an obvious acute subdural or epidural hematoma is not present.  The diffuse abnormal low attentuation to the brain is most indicative of either diffuse hypoperfusion injury or even diffuse acute cortical necrosis.  The pattern of greatest involvement in the posterior half of the brain encompasses a vascular territory for both the posterior cerebral and middlecerebral arteries.  Therefore the extent of the abnormal low attentuation is greater than that can be accounted for by an acute arterial event alone.   This pattern of posterior injury can also be seen as one of the parenchymal manifestations of non-accidental trauma.  Is clear that the pattern of the insult and severity seen on the current imaging study is far greater than we would expect to see with a fall from a parents arm to the floor over a short distance.

EDCTNonTraDescr: 2. There is a lytic lesion within the parietal bone posterior to the fracture site, with a less well-defined lesion on the contralateral side and possible cortical thinning along the anterior aspect of the fracture line. While lucencies in the high parietal bone may be seen with the normal variant of parietal foramina, these lesions have a somewhat atypical appearance for this diagnosis. The possibliity of other lytic lesions of the calvarium, such as Langerhans cell histiocytosis should be considered and perhaps may account for a pathologic fracture as cortical thinning is seen along the fracture line. Further evaluation with a skeletal survey to evaluate for additional bony lesions is suggested.
